The exact error you are getting when calling `Integer.parseInt` might be happening because you never stripped off the parentheses from the string number before attempting to parse it.

Assuming each input line would consist of one or more tuples looking like `(A, B)`, I would suggest the following:

    Scanner inputFile = new Scanner(System.in);
    System.out.println(&quot;File to read from&quot;);
    File file = new File (inputFile.nextLine());
    inputFile = new Scanner(file);
    ArrayList&lt;ponySort&gt; nameAge = new ArrayList&lt;ponySort&gt;();
    
    while (inputFile.hasNextLine()) {
        String currentLine = inputFile.nextLine();
        String[] parts = currentLine.split(&quot;(?&lt;=\\)) (?=\\()&quot;);
        for (String part : parts) {
            String input = part.replaceAll(&quot;[()]&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
            int age = Integer.parseInt(input.split(&quot;, &quot;)[0]);
            String name = input.split(&quot;, &quot;)[1];
            nameAge.add(new ponySort(name, age));
        }
    }

The splitting logic I used takes a single line of one or more tuples, and splits on the space precisely located in between tuples (ignoring other spaces).  Then, we can remove the surrounding parentheses and use the same string splitting logic you were already using.

Note: Java naming convention says that classes should begin with an _uppercase_ letter, so the name `PonySort` should be used instead of `ponySort`.

I think you can just use custom delimeter for `Scanner` and read pair of `int` and `String`:

     final class PonySort {
    
        public static final Comparator&lt;PonySort&gt; SORT_AGE_ASC = Comparator.comparingInt(PonySort::getAge).thenComparing(PonySort::getName);
    
        private final String name;
        private final int age;
    }
    
    public static Set&lt;PonySort&gt; readFile(File file) throws FileNotFoundException {
        try (Scanner scan = new Scanner(file)) {
            scan.useDelimiter(&quot;(\\)\\s+\\()|(,\\s)|\\(|\\)&quot;);
    
            Set&lt;PonySort&gt; nameAge = new TreeSet&lt;&gt;(PonySort.SORT_AGE_ASC);
    
            while (scan.hasNext()) {
                int age = scan.nextInt();
                String name = scan.next();
                nameAge.add(new PonySort(name, age));
            }
    
            return nameAge;
        }
    }

